mRNA splicing
Splicing of mRNA increases the number of dierent
proteins an organism can produce.
Alternative splicing is a process during gene expression whereby a single
gene codes for multiple proteins. This occurs in genes with multiple
exons. A particular exon may or may not be included in the nal
messenger RNA. As a result, the proteins translated from alternatively
spliced mRNAs will differ in their amino acid sequence and possibly in
their biological functions.
In mammals, the protein tropomyosin is encoded by a gene that has
eleven exons. Tropomyosin pre-mRNA is spliced differently in different
tissues resulting in ve different forms of the protein. For example, in
skeletal muscle, exon 2 is missing from the mRNA and in smooth
muscle, exons 3 and 10 are not present.
